{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_3","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/research-synthesis.md\"","aggregated_output":"# WakeTask Research Synthesis\n\nDate: 2026-05-14\n\n## Target user and urgent problem\n- **Target user**: iPhone users (students, shift workers, professionals, ADHD-leaning routine strugglers, heavy sleepers) who regularly snooze, dismiss alarms in sleep inertia, and return to sleep.\n- Urgent problem: default alarm behaviors optimize for sound delivery, not sustained wakefulness; users need a reliable system that ensures they are physically and cognitively awake after alarm dismissal.\n- Market signal: App Store mission-alarm leaders show strong demand, while Reddit users describe active switching due to ad bloat, bypass loopholes, and reliability mistrust.\n\n## Jobs-to-be-done\nPrimary **jobs-to-be-done**:\n1. \"When I am half-asleep, help me wake up in a way I cannot autopilot through.\"\n2. \"After alarm dismissal, keep me awake long enough to avoid relapse sleep.\"\n3. \"Give me strict wake accountability without panic states or creepy tone.\"\n4. \"Work reliably when I travel or change environment (no brittle single-point mission).\"\n5. \"Provide trust-first value without aggressive ads, clutter, or pricing surprises.\"\n\n## Top complaint themes and quoted evidence summaries\n1. Autopilot bypass and relapse sleep\n- Evidence summary: users report they can complete tasks unconsciously and \"have no memory,\" then return to bed.\n- Indicative phrasing from Reddit research: \"my sleepy brain has found a way around it\", \"my problem isn't waking up - it's staying up\".\n\n2. Reliability anxiety and failure intolerance\n- Evidence summary: App Store and Reddit evidence shows users keep backups when alarms crash, background execution fails, or mission completion loops break.\n- High-salience examples: overnight interruption risk and barcode mission edge cases creating panic loops.\n\n3. Monetization and UX trust erosion\n- Evidence summary: repeated complaints about ads, clutter, and subscription shock in wake-critical moments.\n- Indicative phrasing: \"ungodly amount of ads\", \"bloated and too cluttered\", \"just awful pricing\".\n\n4. Tone and privacy discomfort\n- Evidence summary: users react negatively to intimate/creepy notifications and unclear permission purpose.\n- Implication: trust drops quickly when copy tone or permission prompts feel manipulative.\n\n## Competitor strengths and weaknesses\n- **Alarmy (competitor)**\n  - Strengths: strong mission variety, high brand recognition, proven heavy-sleeper positioning.\n  - Weaknesses: ad/pricing frustration, perceived bloat, reliability anxiety in edge cases.\n- **Challenges Alarm Clock (competitor)**\n  - Strengths: clear high-friction challenge USP.\n  - Weaknesses: notification tone quality concerns, limited stay-awake accountability depth.\n- **Instant Wake Up (competitor)**\n  - Strengths: chained mission sequencing valued by heavy sleepers.\n  - Weaknesses: crash/background concerns and brittle barcode flows.\n- **Alarm Clock for Me (competitor)**\n  - Strengths: broad utility feature set and familiarity.\n  - Weaknesses: clutter, ads, sleepy-state interaction risk.\n- **Sleep Cycle / Pillow (adjacent competitors)**\n  - Strengths: polished tracking and insight loops.\n  - Weaknesses: weaker anti-bypass posture for urgent wake-accountability jobs.\n\n## Feature opportunity matrix\n1. Post-dismissal wake assurance\n- User pain: users wake then relapse.\n- Opportunity: mandatory wake-check loop at +3/+7/+12 minutes with escalation.\n- Differentiation: optimize for \"still awake,\" not merely \"alarm dismissed.\"\n\n2. Mission safety rails\n- User pain: panic when mission target fails.\n- Opportunity: pre-validate barcode/QR and provide accountable fallback mission.\n- Differentiation: strictness without trap states.\n\n3. Reliability telemetry as product surface\n- User pain: no trust that alarm stack actually executed as intended.\n- Opportunity: visible morning log (alarm fired time, dismiss time, fallback path used).\n- Differentiation: explicit reliability proof layer.\n\n4. Travel-proof strictness profiles\n- User pain: home-anchored tasks break while traveling.\n- Opportunity: dynamic mission packs by context (home/travel/light sleep debt/high sleep debt).\n- Differentiation: resilient strictness across contexts.\n\n5. Trust-first wake UX and pricing\n- User pain: ad interruptions and pricing surprise during critical wake moments.\n- Opportunity: distraction-minimal wake flow and transparent premium policy.\n- Differentiation: wake-critical trust positioning.\n\n## Differentiation thesis (App Store 4.3 defensibility)\nWakeTask is a focused wake-accountability product, not a clone alarm utility. The core thesis is: **\"reliability-verified, anti-bypass wake completion with post-dismissal accountability.\"**\n\nWhy this is differentiated enough for **App Store** review 4.3 scrutiny:\n- Distinct outcome metric: sustained wakefulness, not alarm playback.\n- Distinct interaction model: two-phase wake flow (dismissal + verification loop).\n- Distinct trust model: reliability telemetry and mission-safe fallback architecture.\n- Distinct product posture: strict but non-creepy coach tone and low-clutter wake UI.\n\n## Design direction\n- **Design** principle: \"3:30am-safe UX\" for sleep inertia.\n- Large tap targets, low-choice alarm screens, clear hierarchy of urgent actions.\n- Visual language: calm high-contrast morning palette; avoid gamified noise during alarm-critical state.\n- Interaction model: progressive friction ladder (light cognitive -> moderate cognitive -> physical validation) rather than one-size hard mode.\n- Voice/tone options: neutral coach, strict coach, minimal prompts.\n\n## MVP scope and non-goals\n### MVP scope\n- Task-gated alarms with chained missions (math/memory/motion/scan).\n- Setup-time mission validation (especially scan assets).\n- Post-dismiss wake-check loop with escalation.\n- Reliability log for each alarm event.\n- Context profiles (weekday/weekend/travel basic presets).\n- Privacy and pricing transparency screens.\n\n### Non-goals (v1)\n- Full sleep-stage analytics platform.\n- Social network/competitive wake communities.\n- Broad wellness content library.\n- Deep wearable biometrics dependency.\n\n## Risks and unknowns\n- **Risk (high)**: iOS background/notification constraints may limit anti-bypass guarantees.\n- **Risk (medium)**: high-friction defaults can increase churn if not calibrated by user type.\n- **Risk (medium)**: strict missions may create household disruption and negative reviews.\n- **Risk (medium)**: camera/permission skepticism can suppress conversion.\n- **Risk (low-medium)**: incumbent brand familiarity may slow acquisition without clear proof-led onboarding.\n\nValidation unknowns for next stage:\n- Best escalation schedule by segment (students vs shift workers).\n- Conversion impact of transparent pricing copy variants.\n- Tolerance thresholds for strictness before uninstall risk spikes.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
