{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_6","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat > .workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec-red-team.md <<'EOF'\n# Spec Red Team Review\n\n## Scope Reviewed\n- \"'`.workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec.md`\n- `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/definition-of-done.md`\n- `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/research-synthesis.md`\n- `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/quality-bar.json`\n\n## Reviewer stance\nSkeptical product, QA, iOS implementation, and App Store 4.3 perspective. Standard applied: reject on any critical ambiguity that could allow template-like output, untestable claims, or unsupported release-readiness claims.\n\n## Rejection Criteria Assessment\n\n### 1) Research evidence too weak to justify product\n**Result: PASS (not rejected)**\n\nWhy:\n- Research synthesis grounds the problem in concrete user pain clusters: autopilot dismissal, relapse sleep, reliability mistrust, ad/pricing trust erosion, and tone/privacy discomfort.\n- Competitive analysis is specific (Alarmy, Challenges Alarm Clock, Instant Wake Up, Alarm Clock for Me, Sleep Cycle/Pillow) and maps strengths/weaknesses to opportunity areas.\n- The differentiation thesis is explicit and outcome-level (sustained wakefulness with post-dismiss verification), not just UI skinning.\n- Evidence gate has already passed and required research artifacts are present.\n\nResidual concern:\n- Research synthesis mostly provides summarized evidence rather than quoted raw excerpts with source density metrics. This is acceptable for spec stage but should be tightened in launch narrative docs.\n\n### 2) Features vague or untestable\n**Result: PASS (not rejected)**\n\nWhy:\n- Acceptance criteria define testable behavior for each core mission type and for fallback behavior.\n- Post-dismiss timing contract is concrete (+3/+7/+12).\n- Reliability telemetry fields are enumerated and tied to UI rendering expectations.\n- Permissions behavior is testable by mission configuration and denial recovery path.\n- Quality gates are explicit and blocking.\n\nResidual concern:\n- Motion mission threshold and escalation policy details are still configurable rather than numerically fixed in spec. This is acceptable if test plans pin values per profile.\n\n### 3) App too template-like\n**Result: PASS (not rejected)**\n\nWhy:\n- Core product loop (mission-gated dismissal + post-dismiss wake verification + reliability log) is clearly differentiated from commodity alarm templates.\n- App Store 4.3 defensibility is called out with specific differentiators.\n- Trust-first wake-critical UX constraints and anti-creepy tone policy materially shape behavior and copy beyond boilerplate defaults.\n\nResidual concern:\n- Differentiation depends on execution quality of wake-check escalation and reliability timeline UX; weak implementation could collapse into a mission-alarm clone.\n\n### 4) Boilerplate reuse unclear\n**Result: PASS (not rejected)**\n\nWhy:\n- Spec explicitly mandates extension of `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution` and lists required reused modules and project surfaces.\n- Definition of Done includes a blocking “boilerplate reuse proof” item and prohibits unauthorized infrastructure rewrites.\n- Quality bar forbidden list reinforces no rebuild of core platform modules without ADR approval.\n\n### 5) Appium exploratory QA not required\n**Result: PASS (not rejected)**\n\nWhy:\n- Spec defines required artifact path, execution expectation, and pass thresholds (`ok=true`, `crashes=0`, `failures=0`, `buttons_tapped>=25`, `screens_visited>=8`).\n- DoD repeats this as a blocking item, allowing deferral only with explicit approved conditions.\n- Quality bar also requires exploratory tapper coverage.\n\n### 6) Release criteria can pass without macOS/Xcode evidence\n**Result: PASS (not rejected)**\n\nWhy:\n- Spec quality gates include `xcodebuild build` and `xcodebuild test` as blocking checks.\n- DoD requires macOS/Xcode execution evidence attached, or explicit approved deferral.\n- Quality bar explicitly forbids claiming iOS validation complete without macOS/GitHub Actions evidence.\n\n## Cross-functional Red-Team Findings\n\n### Product risk\n- The spec is strong on differentiation and trust positioning, but strictness calibration remains a churn risk; segment-based defaults should be validated early.\n\n### QA risk\n- Testability is high overall; mission threshold parametrization must be frozen in test fixtures to avoid interpretation drift.\n\n### iOS implementation risk\n- Background execution constraints are acknowledged; implementation should avoid any implied guaranteed wake claims and preserve fail-safe fallbacks.\n\n### App Store review risk\n- 4.3 positioning is intentionally explicit and should be defensible if metadata and in-app copy consistently emphasize the two-phase accountability model.\n\nVERDICT: APPROVED\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
